        optionStyleType: `st-lower-alpha`,
        answer: [2],
        ansText: `Rationale:- Exposure of this individual to the foreign (horse) proteins in the transferred serum led to the production of antibodies against these proteins and the formation of immune complexes in the circulation. These complexes deposit in blood vessels, preferentially in joints and kidneys, where they activate complement (by the classical pathway) and induce destructive inflammation. Red cells in the urine indicate glomerular injury The activation of complement leads to a fall in the levels of C3, the major complement protein in the blood. This is a classic example of acute serum sickness, a systemic immune complex-mediated disease.`,
