        q: `A 28-year-old man has had hemoptysis and hematuria for the past 2 days. On physical examination, his temperature is 36.8&#176; C, pulse is 87/min, respirations are 19/min, and blood pressure is 150/90 mm Hg. Laboratory studies show creatinine of 3.8 mg/dL (0.6–1.2 mg/dL) and urea nitrogen of 35 mg/dL (7–18 mg/dL). Urinalysis shows 4+ hematuria, 2+ proteinuria, and no glucose. A renal biopsy specimen shows glomerular damage in H&amp;E stained sections and linear deposition of complement C3 and IgG antibody by immunofluorescence. Autoantibodies against which of the following has the greatest specificity for this patient’s condition?`,
        q2: ``,
        q3: [],
        option: [`Glomerular basement membrane (GBM)`, ` DNA topoisomerase 1`,` Double stranded DNA`,` IgM`,`Sj&#246;gren syndrome–related antibody A (SS-A)`],
        optionFeedback: [`The renal manifestations indicate a mix of nephritis (hematuria) and nephrotic syndrome (proteinuria), and the linear pattern of immunofluorescence is characteristic of anti-GBM antibody-mediated disease. Hemoptysis suggests that the antibody has also bound to lung basement membrane, diagnostic of the Goodpasture syndrome, an autoimmune disorder that is much more common in smokers than non-smokers.`,`DNA topoisomerase 1 is found in systemic sclerosis, but not in Goodpasture syndrome.`,`Anti–double stranded DNA is diagnostic of SLE.`,`Anti-IgM antibody is not seen in any autoimmune or allergic disease.`,`Anti–SS-A is found in Sj&#246;gren syndrome and other autoimmune diseases but not in Goodpasture syndrome.`],
