        optionFeedback: [`Antibodies bound to antigens do activate leukocytes via Fc receptors and may cause antibody-dependent cellular cytotoxicity (which may kill infected and tumor cells), but this is not the major reaction for red cell destruction.`,`Immune complex deposition in glomeruli would cause progressive renal disease and not the acute systemic manifestations seen in this patient.`,`The laboratory error likely led to the patient receiving an ABO blood group mismatched blood transfusion. Individuals of a particular ABO blood type have “natural” antibodies against the blood group antigens they do not express, but not against their own blood group antigens (because their own antigens induce tolerance). The mismatched blood probably contained antibodies against the patient’s red cells. These antibodies bound to the red cells, activated complement, and caused massive intravascular hemolysis and systemic inflammation, components of a transfusion reaction.`,`Mast cell degranulation is important in allergic reactions, not transfusion reactions.`,`TNF release is seen in disseminated bacterial infections and is a cause of septic shock.`],
