        q: `A 31-year-old woman has had increasing peripheral edema, pleuritic chest pain, and an erythematous rash for the past 6 months. Laboratory studies show increasing serum creatinine, and urinalysis shows proteinuria with red cell casts. A renal biopsy is performed, and the light microscopic appearance is shown in the figure. Autoantibodies against which of the following, when present, are specific for this patient’s condition?`,
        q2: `<img src="../images/f004-q020-9780323640251.png"/>`,
        q3: [],
        option: [` Centromere`, `Citrullinated peptide`,` DNA topoisomerase I`,` Double-stranded DNA (ds-DNA)`,` Sj&#246;gren syndrome–related antibody A (SS-A)`],
        optionFeedback: [`Anti-centromere antibodies are most often seen in systemic sclerosis.`,`Anti-citrullinated peptide antibodies are seen in rheumatoid arthritis.`,`Anti-DNA topoisomerase antibodies are most often seen in systemic sclerosis.`,`The clinical features should raise the suspicion of systemic lupus erythematosus with lupus nephritis, which would account for the abnormal renal function tests, proteinuria (causing peripheral edema), and microscopic hematuria. The renal histology is classic for diffuse proliferative glomerulonephritis, (Chapter 11) the most common and severe form of lupus nephritis. The most specific antibody in this disease is anti–double stranded DNA antibody.`,`Anti-SS-A antibodies are seen in Sj&#246;gren syndrome.`],
        optionStyleType: `st-upper-alpha`,
