        q: `A 63-year-old man has a 4-month history of increasing malaise and back pain. On physical examination, he is afebrile and shows mild muscle wasting. Laboratory studies are significant for serum creatinine of 4.5 mg/dL (0.6–1.2 mg/dL) and urea nitrogen of 44 mg/dL (7–18 mg/dL). Urine analysis reveals heavy proteinuria and presence of immunoglobulin light chains. A radiograph of his spine shows rounded lucent lesions. The microscopic appearance of his liver with Congo red stain (<i>A</i>) and with polarized light (<i>B</i>) is shown in the figure. Which of the following underlying conditions is most likely to be present in this patient?`,
