        optionFeedback: [`Rheumatoid arthritis also predisposes to amyloidosis but does not cause lytic bone lesions in the vertebral column or excessive production of Ig light chains. Amyloidosis in rheumatoid arthritis is due to overproduction of serum amyloid A protein (SAA).`,`Metastatic prostate cancer may cause vertebral lesions with bone pain, but these are typically osteoblastic instead of osteolytic, and there is no association with renal failure or amyloidosis.`,`Lytic bone lesions and urinary Ig light chains are diagnostic of multiple myeloma. The proteinuria suggests amyloidosis involving the kidneys, and the biopsy appearance is diagnostic for amyloid deposits: on light microscopy, Congo red stains amyloid bright red and with polarization, the deposits appear green.`,`Familial Mediterranean fever also predisposes to amyloidosis but does not cause lytic bone lesions in the vertebral column or excessive production of Ig light chains. Amyloidosis in familial Mediterranean fever is due to overproduction of serum amyloid A protein (SAA).`,`Tuberculosis predisposes to amyloidosis and may cause bone lesions (spinal tuberculosis) but there would not be excess Ig production. Like familial Mediterranean fever, amyloidosis in tuberculosis is due to SAA.`],
