        optionFeedback: [`The clinical picture is characteristic of rheumatoid arthritis complicated by amyloidosis. In inflammatory conditions like this, the amyloid is derived from SAA protein, which is produced as part of the acute-phase response in inflammation. Renal amyloidosis has caused nephrotic syndrome (elevated urine albumin) and renal failure (elevated serum creatinine and blood urea nitrogen)`,`β<sub>2</sub>-microglobulin can also form amyloid deposits. This happens in dialysis patients when plasma β<sub>2</sub>-microglobulin is not adequately cleared through dialysis membranes and accumulates in the blood and tissues (hemodialysis-associated amyloidosis), a complication that has now largely disappeared with current dialysis membranes.`,`Free λ Light chains may be produced in excess in myeloma.`,`Rheumatoid factor is seen in rheumatoid arthritis but does not undergo the improper folding that is a prerequisite for deposition as amyloid.`,`Increased CRP (an acute phase reactant) is seen in rheumatoid arthritis but does not undergo the improper folding that is a prerequisite for deposition as amyloid.`],
