        q: `A 79-year-old man has a 4-year history of worsening congestive heart failure. On physical examination, his temperature is 36.9&#176; C, pulse is 70/min, respirations are 16/min, and blood pressure is 120/75 mm Hg. Imaging and hemodynamic studies suggest the diagnosis of restrictive cardiomyopathy (decreased ventricular compliance, resulting in impaired diastolic ventricular filling during diastole). All laboratory studies, including serum protein electrophoresis and examination of bone marrow smear, are normal. An endomyocardial biopsy specimen shows Congo red–positive interstitial deposits of amorphous material. Which of the following proteins is most likely to be a precursor for this material?`,
        q2: ``,
        q3: [],
        option: [`α-Fetoprotein`, ` β<sub>2</sub>-microglobulin`,` Light chains`,`Transthyretin`,`Troponin T`],
        optionFeedback: [`α-fetoprotein is also a transport protein (made by the liver and elevated in patients with hepatocellular carcinoma) but it does not form amyloid. The deposition of amyloid in the heart makes the wall “stiffer” which is characteristic of restrictive cardiomyopathy.`,`β<sub>2</sub>-microglobulin is the source of amyloid in hemodialysis-associated amyloidosis but this is usually systemic and is not restricted to the heart. With newer dialysis membranes, this complication is extremely uncommon.`,`Ig light chains may be produced in excess in myeloma and related gammopathies and may form amyloid, but this is usually systemic and is not restricted to the heart.`,`Cardiac amyloid is most often derived from the transport protein transthyretin. Why this protein may be produced in excessive amounts or deposits in the form of amyloid, especially in the heart, are not known. The deposition of amyloid in the heart causes restrictive cardiomyopathy.`,`Troponin T is a myocardial protein that is released into the blood following myocardial infarction. It is not a source of amyloid and is not associated with restrictive cardiomyopathy.`],
